node.text:
“My mom was pregnant with me during 9/11, and my father, who was an Air Force pilot for 23 years, was flying an 8 a.m. commercial shuttle from Boston to La Guardia that day,” said Caitlin Beirne ’24, a Theater, Dance & Media concentrator from Long Island. “He turned around the World Trade Center towers about six minutes before the first tower was hit.” Soon after the events of 9/11, he was deployed to the Middle East for six years.⠀
⠀
#Harvard #September11⠀
⠀
Photo: Jon Chase/Harvard Staff Photographer⠀
⠀
---⠀
Harvard College students, who are among the nearly quarter of the American population who were either not alive or are too young to remember 9/11, share how the day nevertheless affected their lives. Read more stories at the link in our bio.

node.accessibility_caption: A man wearing a mask cleans the back of a statue

node.text:
Harvard Yard’s most popular resident, the John Harvard Statue, is nearing 140 years old. Enduring New England weather, excited visitors, and occasional vandals, the iconic statue receives occasional washings by Harvard’s Landscape Services team. But this summer he underwent a careful restoration: a team specializing in the restoration of public monuments restored the original color and shine to the 1884 statue. ⠀
⠀
“We think of the John Harvard Statue as being a kind of stable, forever monument, but this bronze is actually a delicate work of art,” said Angela Chang, a specialist in the conservation of objects and sculpture at the Harvard Art Museums. ⠀
⠀
Check out our Story for a behind-the-scenes look at the restoration of the statue.⠀
⠀
#Harvard #JohnHarvardStatue⠀
⠀
Photos: @stephanie_blair_mitchell/Harvard Staff Photographer

node.text:
Harvard students and alumni volunteered on more than 70 projects during yesterday's Global Day of Service. In Allston, students prepped the Gardner Pilot Academy for the new school year by painting, cleaning up the playground, and gardening. Another group sorted and organized book donations at the Honan-Allston Library, while others cleaned the streets of Harvard Square. ⠀
⠀
#HarvardServes #Harvard⠀
⠀
Photos: Jon Chase/Harvard Staff Photographer

node.accessibility_caption: Matt Tengtrakool, a first-year student, stands amongst flowers in a community garden.

node.text:
More than 120 first-year students participated in Harvard College’s SPARK program this summer, committing 100 hours of community service to their hometowns.⠀
⠀
1) Matt Tengtrakool, an Eagle Scout, tapped into his passion for the environment, nutrition, and education by leading construction of a shaded seating area, including a small pollinator garden and visitor kiosk, in a community garden in his hometown of Burlington, MA. Photo: Kris Snibbe/Harvard Staff Photographer⠀
⠀
2) Daniel Villani spent his summer developing materials for a fundraising campaign for Rochester Community Inclusive Rowing. He says, “It’s been really nice to be able to help them change other people’s lives like they’ve changed mine.” Photo courtesy of Daniel Villani⠀
⠀
3) A resident of South Florida, Alejandra Beltran and her community face hardships each hurricane season, so she decided to reach out to a local women’s shelter that provides sanctuary, support, and  resources to women and children experiencing homelessness, and offered to run a hurricane-preparedness campaign. Photo courtesy of Alejandra Beltran⠀
⠀
#Harvard #Harvard2025 #HarvardInSummer
